    ## Use when
    - A <eds-link eds-href="/components/form/form.html">Form</eds-link>, or section of a <eds-link eds-href="/components/form/form.html">Form</eds-link>, needs a group of <eds-link eds-href="/components/button/button.html#primary-action">Buttons</eds-link> for primary and secondary actions. Examples of these actions include:
        - Submitting data
        - Continuing to the next section.
        - Going back to the previous section.
    - A <eds-link eds-href="/components/form/form.html">Form</eds-link> needs a "tertiary" <eds-link eds-href="/components/button/button.html#tertiary">Button</eds-link> to exit or cancel the engagement.
    - A <eds-link eds-href="/components/form/form.html">Form</eds-link> needs to present additional instructions or disclosures in close proximity to the action <eds-link eds-href="/components/button/button.html">Buttons</eds-link>.

    ## Visual style
    - Always include one primary action inside Form Actions.
    - Always use the "primary" <eds-link eds-href="/components/button/button.html">Button</eds-link> component for actions such as, "Submit," "Next," "Continue," etc.
    - Always use the "secondary" <eds-link eds-href="/components/button/button.html">Button</eds-link> component for actions such as, "Previous," "Go back," etc.
    - Always use the "tertiary" <eds-link eds-href="/components/button/button.html">Button</eds-link> component for actions such as, "Cancel," "Exit," "Save and exit," etc.
    - Never use controls other than <eds-link eds-href="/components/button/button.html">Button</eds-link> inside Form Actions.
    - The top border appears by default to visually separate the Form Actions from the content above it, but it may be removed.

